**File:** `/Users/kevinbarnard/src/minix-4/kernel/src/clock.rs`

Key flow (lines 40-66):
```rust
pub unsafe fn tick() {
    UPTIME.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);

    let Some(cur) = unsafe { sched::current_proc_mut() } else { return; };

    // Print tick identifier
    let id = if cur.name[0] != 0 { cur.name[0] } else { b'?' };
    Uart::new().putc(id);

    if cur.quantum_left > 0 {
        cur.quantum_left -= 1;
    }
    let quantum_expired = cur.quantum_left == 0;
    if quantum_expired {
        cur.rts_flags.fetch_or(RTS_NO_QUANTUM, Ordering::Relaxed);
    }
    // NLL drops cur borrow before reschedule()
    if quantum_expired {
        unsafe { sched::reschedule() };
    }
}
```

**For slice 2.5:** When a process blocks on IPC (SEND/RECEIVE), you don't dequeue it from the run queue immediately—it stays blocked with `RTS_SENDING` or `RTS_RECEIVING` set. On the next timer tick, `pick_proc()` will skip blocked processes and pick the next runnable one. When IPC completes (message delivered), you dequeue the blocked process and re-enqueue it, so `pick_proc()` will eventually run it again.

