In `kernel/src/proc/sched.rs`, add `rts_set` / `rts_unset` as `&mut Proc`-taking helpers that internally call `enqueue(nr)` / `dequeue(nr)` after dropping the borrow.

A new `kernel/src/proc/table.rs` accessor — `proc_table_mut_slice() -> &'static mut [Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS]` (unsafe, single-borrow contract) — lets the IPC code take *one* `&mut [Proc]` and pass it down through every primitive. This is the borrow-pattern key: see §3.

## 2. `Proc` field additions

Add exactly one field to `Proc` (`kernel/src/proc/proc_struct.rs:23-70`):

```rust
/// User-space VA where the next delivered message should land.
/// Set when a process blocks on RECEIVE / SENDREC; consumed by
/// the el1_return_to_user flush path when MF_DELIVERMSG is set.
pub deliver_msg_vir: u64,
```

Default in `Proc::EMPTY`: `deliver_msg_vir: 0`. Touched in three places: written in `mini_receive` (and in `mini_send` immediate-delivery to a waiting receiver — copy from receiver's pre-recorded value, not from the sender), read by the new `flush_deliver_msg(p)` helper invoked from the SVC tail and from `el1_return_to_user`'s Rust-side preamble (see §10).

That is the only struct field change. Everything else MINIX 3 needs (`caller_q`, `q_link`, `send_msg`, `deliver_msg`, `getfrom_e`, `sendto_e`) is already in place per `proc_struct.rs:48-60`.

## 3. `do_ipc` dispatcher

Replace `kernel/src/ipc/mod.rs:33-48` with the following flow. Key insight: all IPC primitives take an explicit `proc_table: &mut [Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS]` slice so they're unit-testable without `PROC_TABLE` (§12). `do_ipc` is the *one and only* place that materializes that slice from the static.

```rust
#[unsafe(no_mangle)]
pub extern "C" fn do_ipc(frame: &mut ArchRegisterFrame) {
    let src_dst_e: Endpoint = frame.x[0] as i32;
    let call_nr: i32       = frame.x[1] as i32;
    let msg_addr: u64      = frame.x[2];

    // SAFETY: SVC entry holds the single-threaded invariant — IRQ delivery
    // is masked (DAIF.I = 1 in EL1) during the entire SVC dispatch; we are
    // the only writer to PROC_TABLE for the duration of the call.
    let table = unsafe { proc_table_mut_slice() };

    // 1. Identify the caller.
    let caller_nr = match current_caller_nr() {
        Some(nr) => nr,
        None => { frame.x[0] = EBADCALL as u64; return; }
    };

    // 2. Validate the IPC trap is one this caller's trap_mask allows. ANY
    //    is only legal with RECEIVE.
    let result: i32 = match call_nr {
        SEND    => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, SEND,    |t| mini_send(t, caller_nr, src_dst_e, msg_addr, SendFlags::Blocking)),
        RECEIVE => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, RECEIVE, |t| mini_receive(t, caller_nr, src_dst_e, msg_addr, RecvFlags::Blocking)),
        SENDREC => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, SENDREC, |t| do_sendrec(t, caller_nr, src_dst_e, msg_addr)),
        NOTIFY  => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, NOTIFY,  |t| mini_notify(t, caller_nr, src_dst_e)),
        SENDNB  => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, SENDNB,  |t| mini_send(t, caller_nr, src_dst_e, msg_addr, SendFlags::NonBlocking)),
        SENDA   => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, SENDA,   |t| mini_senda(t, caller_nr, msg_addr, frame.x[3] as usize)),
        _ => EBADCALL,
    };

    // 3. Return value (only meaningful if caller did NOT block). If caller
    //    is now blocked, this write is harmless — the same register slot
    //    is overwritten when delivery completes (the deliver-msg flush
    //    rewrites m_source/m_type in the user buffer, x0 is the caller's
    //    chosen return semantics).
    frame.x[0] = result as u64;

    // 4. Trace.
    let n = CALL_COUNT.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed) + 1;
    if n % TRACE_EVERY == 0 {
        let _ = writeln!(Uart::new(),
            "[ipc {n}] caller={caller_nr} call={call_nr} target={src_dst_e:#x} result={result}");
    }
}
```

`with_trap_check`:

```rust
fn with_trap_check<F>(table: &mut [Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS], caller_nr: ProcNr, call_nr: i32, f: F) -> i32
where F: FnOnce(&mut [Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS]) -> i32 {
    let caller = &table[proc_index(caller_nr).expect("caller in range")];
    // 1. ANY only legal with RECEIVE.
    // (Specific check on the endpoint argument is in each primitive.)
    // 2. Caller must have a priv slot.
    let Some(priv_id) = caller.priv_id else { return ECALLDENIED; };
    // 3. Trap mask allows this primitive.
    // SAFETY: PRIV_TABLE single-threaded invariant.
    let pr = unsafe { priv_slot_mut(priv_id).expect("priv in range") };
    if pr.trap_mask & (1 << call_nr) == 0 { return ETRAPDENIED; }
    f(table)
}
```

Notes:
- `do_sendrec(t, caller, dst_e, msg_addr)` calls `mini_send(.., NonBlocking-but-error-cascades)` then on `OK` sets `misc_flags |= MF_REPLY_PEND` and calls `mini_receive(.., src_e=dst_e, Blocking)`. MINIX 3 `proc.c:574-604` is the template.
- `with_trap_check` swallows the caller's `Priv` borrow before calling into the primitive (NLL drop), keeping the borrow pattern non-aliasing.
- `ipc_to` enforcement (which target endpoints a sender may reach) lives in `mini_send` / `mini_notify` themselves — at the moment we know the *destination* — not here. Pattern matches MINIX 3 `do_sync_ipc:534-572`.

## 4. The mini_* primitives

### Signatures and pseudocode

```rust
pub fn mini_send(
    table: &mut [Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS],
    caller_nr: ProcNr,
    dst_e: Endpoint,
    user_msg_va: u64,
    flags: SendFlags,
) -> i32 {
    // 1. Decode and validate dst_e -> dst_nr. EBADSRCDST if out of range
    //    or NONE/SELF (the latter would have to be resolved earlier — we
    //    treat SELF as "you can't send to yourself" → EDEADSRCDST).
    // 2. ipc_to bitmap check: caller's priv must permit dst_nr's priv_id.
    //    → ECALLDENIED.
    // 3. Copy the user-mode message into a local Message. EFAULT on bad VA.
    //    Override m_source = caller.endpoint (MINIX 3 enforces this — the
    //    sender cannot spoof the source field).
    // 4. WILLRECEIVE(dst, caller.endpoint)? = dst.rts_flags == RTS_RECEIVING
    //    && !MF_REPLY_PEND-confusing-cases && (dst.getfrom_e == ANY ||
    //    dst.getfrom_e == caller.endpoint). If yes:
    //       - dst.deliver_msg = msg
    //       - dst.misc_flags |= MF_DELIVERMSG
    //       - dst.misc_flags &= !MF_REPLY_PEND
    //       - rts_unset(dst, RTS_RECEIVING) -> enqueue if now runnable
    //       - return OK
    // 5. Non-deliverable & SendFlags::NonBlocking → return ENOTREADY.
    // 6. deadlock_check(table, SEND, caller_nr, dst_e) → return ELOCKED
    //    if cycle (and not the size-2 SEND/RECV pair).
    // 7. Block:
    //       - caller.send_msg = msg
    //       - caller.sendto_e = dst_e
    //       - rts_set(caller, RTS_SENDING) -> dequeue
    //       - append caller_nr to dst.caller_q via dst's q-list and
    //         caller.q_link.
    //       - return OK (caller is now blocked; the synthesized OK in x0
    //         is irrelevant because the SVC return will overwrite x0 on
    //         the next dispatch of this caller anyway — but matches MINIX 3
    //         and keeps the slot deterministic).
}
```

```rust
pub fn mini_receive(
    table: &mut [Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS],
    caller_nr: ProcNr,
    src_e: Endpoint,
    user_msg_va: u64,
    flags: RecvFlags,
) -> i32 {
    // Set caller.deliver_msg_vir = user_msg_va NOW; if a deferred send
    // shows up later, that's where we'll deposit.
    // 1. If caller.rts_flags & RTS_SENDING (mid-SENDREC): skip the
    //    notify/queue checks below, jump straight to "block on receive".
    // 2. Check notify_pending bitmap on caller.priv. If any bit matches
    //    src_e (or ANY): clear bit, BuildNotifyMessage into caller.deliver_msg
    //    with m_source = (the priv slot's owning proc's endpoint), set
    //    MF_DELIVERMSG, return OK.
    // 3. (Skip async pending — senda is stubbed.)
    // 4. Walk caller.caller_q for a sender whose endpoint matches src_e
    //    (or any sender if src_e == ANY). If found:
    //       - caller.deliver_msg = sender.send_msg (with m_source set to
    //         sender.endpoint).
    //       - caller.misc_flags |= MF_DELIVERMSG
    //       - rts_unset(sender, RTS_SENDING) -> enqueue sender
    //       - splice sender out of caller_q via q_link manipulation.
    //       - if (caller was mid-SENDREC) clear MF_REPLY_PEND.
    //       - return OK.
    // 5. Nothing to deliver:
    //    - RecvFlags::NonBlocking → return ENOTREADY.
    //    - deadlock_check(table, RECEIVE, caller_nr, src_e) → ELOCKED
    //    - Block: caller.getfrom_e = src_e; rts_set(caller, RTS_RECEIVING).
    //    - return OK.
}
```

```rust
pub fn mini_notify(
    table: &mut [Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS],
    caller_nr: ProcNr,
    dst_e: Endpoint,
) -> i32 {
    // 1. Decode dst_e -> dst_nr. EBADSRCDST if out of range.
    // 2. ipc_to enforcement (caller.priv.ipc_to bit for dst.priv_id).
    //    → ECALLDENIED.
    // 3. WILLRECEIVE(dst, caller.endpoint) && !(dst.misc_flags & MF_REPLY_PEND)?
    //    Yes: BuildNotifyMessage into dst.deliver_msg
    //         (m_source = caller.endpoint, m_type = NOTIFY_MESSAGE),
    //         set MF_DELIVERMSG on dst, rts_unset(dst, RTS_RECEIVING).
    //         return OK.
    //    No:  set_sys_bit(dst.priv.notify_pending, caller.priv.id).
    //         return OK.
}

pub fn mini_senda(_: &mut [Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS], _: ProcNr, _: u64, _: usize) -> i32 {
    // TODO(slice 2.6+): walk asynmsg_t table in user memory; honor AMF_*
    // flags, set caller.asyn_pending bits. Slice 2.5's milestone is
    // synchronous IPC ping-pong; async send is unobservable until the
    // SYSTEM task RECEIVEs from it.
    ENOSYS
}
```

### Error returns by primitive

| Primitive | OK paths | Error returns |
|---|---|---|
| SEND  | immediate delivery; deferred (blocked) | EBADSRCDST (bad dst), ECALLDENIED (ipc_to bit clear), EFAULT (user buffer), EDEADSRCDST (size-3+ cycle → ELOCKED actually; EDEADSRCDST is for dead endpoint), ELOCKED (deadlock_check) |
| RECEIVE | immediate notify / queued sender / deferred | EBADSRCDST (bad src), EFAULT, ELOCKED |
| SENDREC | SEND-half + RECEIVE-half | union of the above |
| NOTIFY | never blocks | EBADSRCDST, ECALLDENIED |
| SENDNB | immediate delivery only | EBADSRCDST, ECALLDENIED, EFAULT, ENOTREADY |
| SENDA | none in 2.5 | ENOSYS |

### Key edge cases

- **SELF endpoint to SEND**: MINIX 3 forbids it — returns `EDEADSRCDST` from `deadlock_check` (the trivial size-1 cycle). Reproduce.
- **Receiver going from RTS_RECEIVING+RTS_SENDING (mid-SENDREC) → unblock**: don't enqueue until *both* bits clear. `rts_unset` handles this naturally: it only enqueues when the post-clear value is zero.
- **`mini_receive` walking `caller_q`**: if `src_e == ANY`, pick the head. If specific, walk the linked list; record `prev` so the splice is O(1) once the match is found.
- **Sender's `send_msg.m_source` field**: set by `mini_send` when copying user message in, so the receiver sees the authoritative endpoint. *Receivers cannot trust the m_source on incoming user-supplied messages otherwise.*
- **`m_type` for NOTIFY**: MINIX 3's `BuildNotifyMessage` (proc.c:1135-1148) sets `m_type = NOTIFY_MESSAGE` (defined as `0x1000` in com.h) and zeros payload except for `m_notify.timestamp` (CLOCK only). Slice 2.5 doesn't have a clock-sourced notify, so we copy MINIX 3 verbatim minus the timestamp.
- **SENDREC reply-pend handling**: on the SEND half of SENDREC, mark `MF_REPLY_PEND`. The RECEIVE half clears it when it observes a delivered message from the SENDREC partner. This is the bit that lets a receiver detect "this is a reply, not a fresh request" later (irrelevant in slice 2.5's two-stub demo, but the bookkeeping must be right).

## 5. Run-queue helpers (rts_set / rts_unset)

Add to `kernel/src/proc/sched.rs` (after `dequeue`):

```rust
/// Set bits in `p.rts_flags`; if the process transitions from runnable
/// (all-clear) to blocked, splice it out of the run queue.
///
/// Caller pattern: hold `&mut Proc` to the affected slot, call this, then
/// drop the borrow before any subsequent `sched::*` call that re-borrows
/// the same slot.
///
/// SAFETY: single-threaded boot/IRQ-masked invariant; the run-queue and
/// proc-table writes are sequenced by NLL — we mutate `p.rts_flags`,
/// capture the post-state and `p.nr`, drop the borrow implicitly, then
/// re-enter via the `nr` to manipulate the run queue.
pub unsafe fn rts_set(p: &mut Proc, flag: u32) {
    let was_runnable = p.rts_flags.load(Ordering::Relaxed) == 0;
    p.rts_flags.fetch_or(flag, Ordering::Relaxed);
    let nr = p.nr;                       // capture before NLL drop
    let _ = p;                           // (NLL ends the borrow here)
    if was_runnable {
        // SAFETY: caller's invariants — no other PROC_TABLE borrow live.
        unsafe { dequeue(nr) }
    }
}

pub unsafe fn rts_unset(p: &mut Proc, flag: u32) {
    let prev = p.rts_flags.fetch_and(!flag, Ordering::Relaxed);
    let nr = p.nr;
    let now_runnable = (prev & !flag) == 0;
    let _ = p;
    if now_runnable && (prev != 0) {
        // SAFETY: same.
        unsafe { enqueue(nr) }
    }
}
```

Use sites (all in `ipc/*`):
- `mini_send` immediate delivery: `unsafe { rts_unset(dst, RTS_RECEIVING) }`.
- `mini_send` deferred path: `unsafe { rts_set(caller, RTS_SENDING) }`.
- `mini_receive` immediate from caller_q: `unsafe { rts_unset(sender, RTS_SENDING) }`.
- `mini_receive` deferred: `unsafe { rts_set(caller, RTS_RECEIVING) }`.
- `mini_notify` immediate: `unsafe { rts_unset(dst, RTS_RECEIVING) }`.

Note that the existing `enqueue`/`dequeue` (sched.rs:90-164) take `ProcNr` and re-borrow through `proc_slot_mut`. The capture-`nr`-then-drop pattern is exactly how `clock::tick` (clock.rs:43-64) already handles the same problem (`let quantum_expired = cur.quantum_left == 0;` then drops `cur` before calling `sched::reschedule()`). Reuse the pattern.

## 6. User-memory copy

```rust
// kernel/src/ipc/message.rs

use minix4_kernel_shared::error::{EFAULT, OK};
use minix4_kernel_shared::message::Message;

/// User VA range. T0SZ=16 in TCR_EL1 (asserted in `mmu::assert_tcr_el1_ttbr0_ready`)
/// means the TTBR0 walk covers `[0, 2^48)`. We restrict further to a sane
/// upper bound below the kernel's HHDM (which Limine places at the very
/// high half via TTBR1). Anything in `[0, USER_VA_TOP)` walks through our
/// TTBR0.
pub const USER_VA_TOP: u64 = 1 << 48;

#[inline]
fn user_va_ok(va: u64, len: usize) -> bool {
    let end = va.checked_add(len as u64);
    matches!(end, Some(e) if e <= USER_VA_TOP)
        && va >= core::mem::align_of::<Message>() as u64  // reject NULL & sub-align
}

/// Copy a Message out of user memory.
///
/// SAFETY surrounding `read_volatile`: we hold the single-threaded SVC
/// invariant; the user TTBR0 is the one we installed in
/// `userland_bootstrap`. If `va` points into an unmapped page, the EL1
/// access faults and we panic via `el1_sync_unexpected` (acceptable for
/// slice 2.5; slice 2.6+ adds a per-fault handler that recovers and
/// returns EFAULT).
pub(crate) fn copy_msg_from_user(va: u64) -> Result<Message, i32> {
    if !user_va_ok(va, core::mem::size_of::<Message>()) { return Err(EFAULT); }
    // SAFETY: bounds-checked; aligned (Message is 8-aligned, stub stacks
    // are 16-aligned by construction). Single-threaded.
    let m = unsafe { core::ptr::read_volatile(va as *const Message) };
    Ok(m)
}

pub(crate) fn copy_msg_to_user(va: u64, m: &Message) -> Result<(), i32> {
    if !user_va_ok(va, core::mem::size_of::<Message>()) { return Err(EFAULT); }
    // SAFETY: same.
    unsafe { core::ptr::write_volatile(va as *mut Message, *m); }
    Ok(())
}
```

Bounds: deliberately coarse. The two stub stacks live at `0x80_0000`/`0x81_0000` per `userland.rs:42-49`; both are well below `USER_VA_TOP`. A real per-process VM check arrives in Phase 3.

