## 9. Deadlock algorithm

```rust
// kernel/src/ipc/deadlock.rs

use minix4_kernel_shared::ipc_const::{RECEIVE, SEND};
use minix4_kernel_shared::endpoint::{endpoint_proc, Endpoint};
use crate::proc::flags::{RTS_RECEIVING, RTS_SENDING};
use crate::proc::Proc;
use crate::proc::table::{N_PROC_SLOTS, proc_index};

/// Mirrors MINIX 3 `proc.c:713 deadlock()`. Returns true iff blocking
/// `caller_nr` on `target_e` under primitive `function` (SEND or RECEIVE)
/// would create a cyclic dependency that is NOT the legal size-2
/// SEND↔RECEIVE pair.
pub fn deadlock_check(
    table: &[Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS],
    function: i32,
    caller_nr: ProcNr,
    target_e: Endpoint,
) -> bool {
    let caller = &table[proc_index(caller_nr).expect("caller")];
    let mut group: u32 = 1;
    let mut cur_e = target_e;

    loop {
        let cur_nr = endpoint_proc(cur_e);
        let Some(idx) = proc_index(cur_nr) else { return false; }; // unreachable / dead
        let xp = &table[idx];
        group += 1;

        // The size-2 SEND↔RECEIVE pair is legal. MINIX 3 trick:
        //   if (xp->rts_flags ^ (function << 2)) & RTS_SENDING == 0 ...
        // Where function << 2 turns SEND(=1) into RTS_SENDING(=4) and
        // RECEIVE(=2) into RTS_RECEIVING(=8). For the chain to be legal
        // at this hop, xp's blocking bit must be the *opposite* of what
        // function would set on the caller. Group size 2 (caller + xp)
        // and that orientation = legal pair, not a deadlock.
        let xp_rts = xp.rts_flags.load(Ordering::Relaxed);
        if group == 2 && (xp_rts ^ ((function as u32) << 2)) & RTS_SENDING == 0 {
            return false;
        }

        // Follow xp's blocked-on edge.
        let next_e = if xp_rts & RTS_SENDING != 0 {
            xp.sendto_e
        } else if xp_rts & RTS_RECEIVING != 0 {
            xp.getfrom_e
        } else {
            // Not blocked — chain terminates; no cycle.
            return false;
        };

        if endpoint_proc(next_e) == caller_nr {
            // Closed the loop back to caller and it isn't the legal 2-cycle.
            return true;
        }
        if group > N_PROC_SLOTS as u32 { return true; }  // safety net
        cur_e = next_e;
    }
}
```

**The `function<<2` trick explained.** `SEND=1 << 2 = 4 = RTS_SENDING`. `RECEIVE=2 << 2 = 8 = RTS_RECEIVING`. The XOR yields zero exactly when `xp`'s RTS bit is the *opposite* of the operation the caller is about to do. So for a size-2 chain in which the caller wants to SEND and `xp` is RECEIVING (the classic pair), the bits align — that's a legal mutual rendezvous, not a deadlock. For the ping-pong case slice 2.5 exercises (A SENDRECs B; B RECEIVEs from ANY then SENDs back), the SEND half of A's SENDREC checks `deadlock(SEND, A, B)`. If B is `RTS_RECEIVING` (which is exactly the expected state once B has caught up to its receive), the size-2 trick kicks in and SEND proceeds. If B happens to not be receiving yet (queue cold), the chain terminates one hop in (B is unblocked, `RTS_SENDING=0` and `RTS_RECEIVING=0`), returns `false` (no deadlock), and A blocks normally.

## 10. MF_DELIVERMSG flush path

MINIX 3 flushes `p_delivermsg → p_delivermsg_vir` inside `switch_to_user → delivermsg` (proc.c:1640-1660). MINIX 4 needs the same: after `do_ipc` returns and before `eret`, plus on the first scheduler entry / context switches.

**Hook point.** Add a Rust helper:

```rust
// kernel/src/ipc/mod.rs (or a new flush.rs)
use crate::proc::flags::MF_DELIVERMSG;
use crate::proc::Proc;

/// If `p` has a delivered IPC message pending, copy it into the user's
/// buffer and clear MF_DELIVERMSG. Called immediately before any return
/// path from EL1 to EL0 — both the SVC tail and the timer-IRQ
/// reschedule.
pub fn flush_deliver_msg(p: &mut Proc) {
    if p.misc_flags & MF_DELIVERMSG == 0 { return; }
    // Copy deliver_msg into the user buffer at deliver_msg_vir.
    let va = p.deliver_msg_vir;
    let _ = crate::ipc::message::copy_msg_to_user(va, &p.deliver_msg);
    // (slice 2.5: ignore EFAULT — userland_bootstrap guarantees the buffer
    //  lives in stack page. slice 2.6+: set MF_MSGFAILED on error.)
    p.misc_flags &= !MF_DELIVERMSG;
}
```

**Two call sites:**

(i) **SVC tail** (`trap.S:92-95`). Today the SVC handler is:
```
bl  do_ipc
b   el1_return_to_user
```
Change to:
```
bl  do_ipc
bl  el1_flush_current     // new C-ABI Rust shim
b   el1_return_to_user
```
where `el1_flush_current` is:
```rust
#[unsafe(no_mangle)]
pub extern "C" fn el1_flush_current() {
    // SAFETY: SVC dispatch context, same invariant as do_ipc.
    if let Some(p) = unsafe { crate::proc::sched::current_proc_mut() } {
        crate::ipc::flush_deliver_msg(p);
    }
}
```
That covers the SEND/RECEIVE/SENDREC immediate-delivery cases.

(ii) **Scheduler `reschedule`** (`sched.rs:243-271`): after `pick_proc` selects `next_nr` and before `set_tpidr_to(next)`, call `flush_deliver_msg(next)` so a process woken by the IRQ-driven reschedule path also gets its message copied out. Add inside the `unsafe { let next = proc_slot_mut(next_nr)... }` block, before `set_tpidr_to(next)`.

(iii) `sched::run` (sched.rs:217-227) — first entry to EL0 — should also call `flush_deliver_msg(first)`, defensively, even though no delivery can yet have happened (the stubs haven't run). One-liner; keeps the invariant uniform: "every transition into EL0 flushes any pending delivery".

**Why not put the flush in `el1_return_to_user` (assembly)?** Avoids needing the assembly to know about `MF_DELIVERMSG`, `deliver_msg_vir`, `Message` layout, or the Rust `copy_msg_to_user` bounds check. The shim is one `bl` and Rust owns the policy.

