## 3. `do_ipc` dispatcher

Replace `kernel/src/ipc/mod.rs:33-48` with the following flow. Key insight: all IPC primitives take an explicit `proc_table: &mut [Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS]` slice so they're unit-testable without `PROC_TABLE` (§12). `do_ipc` is the *one and only* place that materializes that slice from the static.

```rust
#[unsafe(no_mangle)]
pub extern "C" fn do_ipc(frame: &mut ArchRegisterFrame) {
    let src_dst_e: Endpoint = frame.x[0] as i32;
    let call_nr: i32       = frame.x[1] as i32;
    let msg_addr: u64      = frame.x[2];

    // SAFETY: SVC entry holds the single-threaded invariant — IRQ delivery
    // is masked (DAIF.I = 1 in EL1) during the entire SVC dispatch; we are
    // the only writer to PROC_TABLE for the duration of the call.
    let table = unsafe { proc_table_mut_slice() };

    // 1. Identify the caller.
    let caller_nr = match current_caller_nr() {
        Some(nr) => nr,
        None => { frame.x[0] = EBADCALL as u64; return; }
    };

    // 2. Validate the IPC trap is one this caller's trap_mask allows. ANY
    //    is only legal with RECEIVE.
    let result: i32 = match call_nr {
        SEND    => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, SEND,    |t| mini_send(t, caller_nr, src_dst_e, msg_addr, SendFlags::Blocking)),
        RECEIVE => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, RECEIVE, |t| mini_receive(t, caller_nr, src_dst_e, msg_addr, RecvFlags::Blocking)),
        SENDREC => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, SENDREC, |t| do_sendrec(t, caller_nr, src_dst_e, msg_addr)),
        NOTIFY  => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, NOTIFY,  |t| mini_notify(t, caller_nr, src_dst_e)),
        SENDNB  => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, SENDNB,  |t| mini_send(t, caller_nr, src_dst_e, msg_addr, SendFlags::NonBlocking)),
        SENDA   => with_trap_check(table, caller_nr, SENDA,   |t| mini_senda(t, caller_nr, msg_addr, frame.x[3] as usize)),
        _ => EBADCALL,
    };

    // 3. Return value (only meaningful if caller did NOT block). If caller
    //    is now blocked, this write is harmless — the same register slot
    //    is overwritten when delivery completes (the deliver-msg flush
    //    rewrites m_source/m_type in the user buffer, x0 is the caller's
    //    chosen return semantics).
    frame.x[0] = result as u64;

    // 4. Trace.
    let n = CALL_COUNT.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed) + 1;
    if n % TRACE_EVERY == 0 {
        let _ = writeln!(Uart::new(),
            "[ipc {n}] caller={caller_nr} call={call_nr} target={src_dst_e:#x} result={result}");
    }
}
```

`with_trap_check`:

```rust
fn with_trap_check<F>(table: &mut [Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS], caller_nr: ProcNr, call_nr: i32, f: F) -> i32
where F: FnOnce(&mut [Proc; N_PROC_SLOTS]) -> i32 {
    let caller = &table[proc_index(caller_nr).expect("caller in range")];
    // 1. ANY only legal with RECEIVE.
    // (Specific check on the endpoint argument is in each primitive.)
    // 2. Caller must have a priv slot.
    let Some(priv_id) = caller.priv_id else { return ECALLDENIED; };
    // 3. Trap mask allows this primitive.
    // SAFETY: PRIV_TABLE single-threaded invariant.
    let pr = unsafe { priv_slot_mut(priv_id).expect("priv in range") };
    if pr.trap_mask & (1 << call_nr) == 0 { return ETRAPDENIED; }
    f(table)
}
```

Notes:
- `do_sendrec(t, caller, dst_e, msg_addr)` calls `mini_send(.., NonBlocking-but-error-cascades)` then on `OK` sets `misc_flags |= MF_REPLY_PEND` and calls `mini_receive(.., src_e=dst_e, Blocking)`. MINIX 3 `proc.c:574-604` is the template.
- `with_trap_check` swallows the caller's `Priv` borrow before calling into the primitive (NLL drop), keeping the borrow pattern non-aliasing.
- `ipc_to` enforcement (which target endpoints a sender may reach) lives in `mini_send` / `mini_notify` themselves — at the moment we know the *destination* — not here. Pattern matches MINIX 3 `do_sync_ipc:534-572`.

