|---|---|---|
| SEND  | immediate delivery; deferred (blocked) | EBADSRCDST (bad dst), ECALLDENIED (ipc_to bit clear), EFAULT (user buffer), EDEADSRCDST (size-3+ cycle → ELOCKED actually; EDEADSRCDST is for dead endpoint), ELOCKED (deadlock_check) |
| RECEIVE | immediate notify / queued sender / deferred | EBADSRCDST (bad src), EFAULT, ELOCKED |
| SENDREC | SEND-half + RECEIVE-half | union of the above |
| NOTIFY | never blocks | EBADSRCDST, ECALLDENIED |
| SENDNB | immediate delivery only | EBADSRCDST, ECALLDENIED, EFAULT, ENOTREADY |
| SENDA | none in 2.5 | ENOSYS |

### Key edge cases

- **SELF endpoint to SEND**: MINIX 3 forbids it — returns `EDEADSRCDST` from `deadlock_check` (the trivial size-1 cycle). Reproduce.
- **Receiver going from RTS_RECEIVING+RTS_SENDING (mid-SENDREC) → unblock**: don't enqueue until *both* bits clear. `rts_unset` handles this naturally: it only enqueues when the post-clear value is zero.
- **`mini_receive` walking `caller_q`**: if `src_e == ANY`, pick the head. If specific, walk the linked list; record `prev` so the splice is O(1) once the match is found.
- **Sender's `send_msg.m_source` field**: set by `mini_send` when copying user message in, so the receiver sees the authoritative endpoint. *Receivers cannot trust the m_source on incoming user-supplied messages otherwise.*
- **`m_type` for NOTIFY**: MINIX 3's `BuildNotifyMessage` (proc.c:1135-1148) sets `m_type = NOTIFY_MESSAGE` (defined as `0x1000` in com.h) and zeros payload except for `m_notify.timestamp` (CLOCK only). Slice 2.5 doesn't have a clock-sourced notify, so we copy MINIX 3 verbatim minus the timestamp.
- **SENDREC reply-pend handling**: on the SEND half of SENDREC, mark `MF_REPLY_PEND`. The RECEIVE half clears it when it observes a delivered message from the SENDREC partner. This is the bit that lets a receiver detect "this is a reply, not a fresh request" later (irrelevant in slice 2.5's two-stub demo, but the bookkeeping must be right).

## 5. Run-queue helpers (rts_set / rts_unset)

Add to `kernel/src/proc/sched.rs` (after `dequeue`):

```rust
/// Set bits in `p.rts_flags`; if the process transitions from runnable
/// (all-clear) to blocked, splice it out of the run queue.
///
/// Caller pattern: hold `&mut Proc` to the affected slot, call this, then
/// drop the borrow before any subsequent `sched::*` call that re-borrows
/// the same slot.
///
/// SAFETY: single-threaded boot/IRQ-masked invariant; the run-queue and
/// proc-table writes are sequenced by NLL — we mutate `p.rts_flags`,
/// capture the post-state and `p.nr`, drop the borrow implicitly, then
/// re-enter via the `nr` to manipulate the run queue.
pub unsafe fn rts_set(p: &mut Proc, flag: u32) {
    let was_runnable = p.rts_flags.load(Ordering::Relaxed) == 0;
    p.rts_flags.fetch_or(flag, Ordering::Relaxed);
    let nr = p.nr;                       // capture before NLL drop
    let _ = p;                           // (NLL ends the borrow here)
    if was_runnable {
        // SAFETY: caller's invariants — no other PROC_TABLE borrow live.
        unsafe { dequeue(nr) }
    }
}

pub unsafe fn rts_unset(p: &mut Proc, flag: u32) {
    let prev = p.rts_flags.fetch_and(!flag, Ordering::Relaxed);
    let nr = p.nr;
    let now_runnable = (prev & !flag) == 0;
    let _ = p;
    if now_runnable && (prev != 0) {
        // SAFETY: same.
        unsafe { enqueue(nr) }
    }
}
```

Use sites (all in `ipc/*`):
- `mini_send` immediate delivery: `unsafe { rts_unset(dst, RTS_RECEIVING) }`.
- `mini_send` deferred path: `unsafe { rts_set(caller, RTS_SENDING) }`.
- `mini_receive` immediate from caller_q: `unsafe { rts_unset(sender, RTS_SENDING) }`.
- `mini_receive` deferred: `unsafe { rts_set(caller, RTS_RECEIVING) }`.
- `mini_notify` immediate: `unsafe { rts_unset(dst, RTS_RECEIVING) }`.

Note that the existing `enqueue`/`dequeue` (sched.rs:90-164) take `ProcNr` and re-borrow through `proc_slot_mut`. The capture-`nr`-then-drop pattern is exactly how `clock::tick` (clock.rs:43-64) already handles the same problem (`let quantum_expired = cur.quantum_left == 0;` then drops `cur` before calling `sched::reschedule()`). Reuse the pattern.

## 6. User-memory copy

```rust
// kernel/src/ipc/message.rs

use minix4_kernel_shared::error::{EFAULT, OK};
use minix4_kernel_shared::message::Message;

/// User VA range. T0SZ=16 in TCR_EL1 (asserted in `mmu::assert_tcr_el1_ttbr0_ready`)
/// means the TTBR0 walk covers `[0, 2^48)`. We restrict further to a sane
/// upper bound below the kernel's HHDM (which Limine places at the very
/// high half via TTBR1). Anything in `[0, USER_VA_TOP)` walks through our
/// TTBR0.
pub const USER_VA_TOP: u64 = 1 << 48;

#[inline]
fn user_va_ok(va: u64, len: usize) -> bool {
    let end = va.checked_add(len as u64);
    matches!(end, Some(e) if e <= USER_VA_TOP)
        && va >= core::mem::align_of::<Message>() as u64  // reject NULL & sub-align
}

/// Copy a Message out of user memory.
///
/// SAFETY surrounding `read_volatile`: we hold the single-threaded SVC
/// invariant; the user TTBR0 is the one we installed in
/// `userland_bootstrap`. If `va` points into an unmapped page, the EL1
/// access faults and we panic via `el1_sync_unexpected` (acceptable for
/// slice 2.5; slice 2.6+ adds a per-fault handler that recovers and
/// returns EFAULT).
pub(crate) fn copy_msg_from_user(va: u64) -> Result<Message, i32> {
    if !user_va_ok(va, core::mem::size_of::<Message>()) { return Err(EFAULT); }
    // SAFETY: bounds-checked; aligned (Message is 8-aligned, stub stacks
    // are 16-aligned by construction). Single-threaded.
    let m = unsafe { core::ptr::read_volatile(va as *const Message) };
    Ok(m)
}

pub(crate) fn copy_msg_to_user(va: u64, m: &Message) -> Result<(), i32> {
    if !user_va_ok(va, core::mem::size_of::<Message>()) { return Err(EFAULT); }
    // SAFETY: same.
    unsafe { core::ptr::write_volatile(va as *mut Message, *m); }
    Ok(())
}
```

Bounds: deliberately coarse. The two stub stacks live at `0x80_0000`/`0x81_0000` per `userland.rs:42-49`; both are well below `USER_VA_TOP`. A real per-process VM check arrives in Phase 3.

